  "notes": "Key triage decisions and ambiguous calls:\n\n1. TICKET 014 (API rate limits): Classified as bug-report rather than billing-other because the core issue is a technical limitation (rate limits blocking ingestion), not a billing dispute. Marked urgent because it's actively blocking a $48k/yr customer's nightly data pipeline and they have a quarterly review deadline. Tickets 023 and 030 are follow-ups from the same org (ops@major-customer.com) about the same rate-limit issue — marked as duplicates of 014.\n\n2. TICKET 007 and 011: Same underlying issue (dashboard sharing permission bug) reported by two people on the same team (mid-co.com, account MC-3309). Ticket 007 is the original report from the affected user; 011 is the sharer's perspective. Marked 011 as duplicate_of 007.\n\n3. TICKET 028 (security-incident): Marked urgent — active account compromise with unauthorized API key usage from foreign IPs. Requires immediate account freeze and key revocation.\n\n4. TICKET 029 (extortion email): Classified as spam-or-noise, not security-incident. This is a classic extortion attempt with a BTC address and a fake vulnerability claim. No legitimate vuln disclosure process is being followed. Do not engage; forward to legal/security team for record-keeping.\n\n5. TICKET 004 (Pixar collectables): Obvious spam/fictitious request. No such program exists. Marked spam-or-noise.\n\n6. TICKET 016 (500 errors on /api/v2/exports): Classified as incident-active (not bug-report) because it describes an ongoing outage with a specific start time and active impact on a SOC1 review. Urgent.\n\n7. TICKET 003 (production down, cannot login): Classified as incident-active and urgent. Entire org locked out with 503s, board meeting imminent.\n\n8. TICKET 022 (refund for downtime): Classified as billing-refund (credit request for service outage). Not marked urgent because the outage has already passed (status page confirms it was over the weekend).\n\n9. TICKET 019 (GDPR request): Classified as legal-compliance with normal urgency. The 30-day GDPR response window provides some buffer, but should be routed to legal/compliance team promptly.\n\n10. TICKET 013 (accidental upgrade refund): Classified as billing-refund. The customer wants both a plan downgrade AND a refund of the difference. Normal urgency — not time-critical but should be handled within a business day.\n\n11. TICKET 010 (podcast pitch) and 018 (acquisition inquiry): Both classified as external-business. Neither is customer support. Low urgency — forward to appropriate internal teams (marketing/sales and founder/exec respectively).\n\nRecommended processing order for urgent items:\n  1. 028 — Security incident (freeze account, revoke keys)\n  2. 003 — Production outage (entire org locked out)\n  3. 016 — API 500 errors (SOC1 review deadline)\n  4. 014/023/030 — Rate limit blocking $48k customer (escalate to eng + account exec)\n  5. 019 — GDPR request (route to legal)"
